    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-08-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-08-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="109"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d109">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/1406.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador to Russia</gloss>
                        to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Summary.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">St. Petersburg</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-08-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 3, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have today received the following aide-mémoire: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Summary of the aide-mémoire: The Ministry for Foreign Affairs
                            acknowledges the embassy’s aide-memoire of July 30 relating to
                            recognition of the Chinese Republican Government. This Government is
                            only provisional; the period for which it was elected soon expires;
                            under its administration the conditions in China seem not to have
                            sensibly improved; the Russian Government believes that none of the
                            powers who have sent troops to China is thinking of recalling them.
                            Consequently the Russian Government believes that it would be prudent to
                            postpone formal recognition of the Chinese Republic until that
                            Government, having been definitely established, shall have given
                            sufficient proofs to judge of its stability.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Guild</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
